* Oyku (Yeni bir ders surusu basladi. Ders suruleri arasindaki sinir komsusu yani)
http://www.chess.com/chessmentor/view_lesson?id=447
Labourdonnais-McDonnell, London 1834 -- World Champions at their Best (1)
From the 1st Match, 3rd Match Game. 
Though no official World Championship title existed at this time, the
Frenchman Labourdonnais (1797-1840) was universally accepted as the finest
player in the world. When England's best player -- McDonnell (1798-1835)
challenged this view, a classic set of six matches was arranged between the
two, totaling 85 games in all!  

Labourdonnais' decisive victory in these matches (plus 18!) made the
Frenchman a legend in his own time. In fact, up to the emergence of Morphy
in 1858, many people felt that Labourdonnais' strength would never be
equaled.  

Once wealthy, Labourdonnais somehow lost his fortune and was reduced to
playing chess for money at the end of his life. In fact, things got so
desperate that he began to sell all his possessions (he even sold his
clothes!) so that he could feed his wife and himself. Poor Labourdonnais,
faced with eviction and starvation and consumed by a number of illnesses,
died in a Parisian garret in 1840.  

The rules for these matches stated that no color change would occur if a
draw resulted. After Labourdonnais drew the first game with the White
pieces he was given White again. After the second game was also drawn he
was given White for a third time. In the present position (which was the
third game of the match and was reached after 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 exd4
4.Bc4 Qf6 5.0-0 d6 6.c3 d3 7.Qxd3 Qg6 8.Bf4 Be7 9.Nbd2 Nh6 10.Rae1 0-0
11.Nd4 Ne5 12.Bxe5 dxe5 13.N4f3 Bd6 14.h3 Kh8 15.Nh4 Qh5 16.Qg3 f5 17.Nxf5
Nxf5 18.exf5 Bxf5 19.Ne4 Bxe4 20.Rxe4 Rf6 21.Rh4 Qf5 22.Qe3 Qd7 23.Bd3 g6
24.Be4 Raf8 25.Qg3 Qg7 26.b4 a5 27.a3 axb4 28.axb4 c5 29.Rb1 cxb4 30.cxb4
Bc7 31.Kh1 Rb6 32.b5 Bd8 33.Rg4 g5 34.Bf3 h5 35.Re4 g4 36.hxg4 hxg4 37.Qxg4
Rh6+ 38.Kg1 Qh7 39.g3 Rg8 40.Qc8 Bb6 41.Qc3 Rxg3+ 42.Kf1 Bd4 43.Qc8+ Rg8
44.Qc4 Rh1+ 45.Ke2 Rxb1) things look completely hopeless for
Labourdonnais. He is a Rook down and his King also doesn't appear to be
very comfortable. How did he save himself?

---------------------------------------------------------
Labourdonnais was a proud man who usually was in good cheer. However, when he was losing, his personality would change and he would begin to swear endless oaths. We can only guess what he sounded like when he reached the poor position featured in this problem!

1.Rxd4! gives up another Rook so that the long diagonal to the Black King
can be utilized. This kind of desperate measure is called for since normal
moves would just be waiting for the ax to fall. 

1...Rb2+ is the best winning try. Black remains up an Exchange but finds
that the resulting position is probably impossible to win.  

For the crucial capture of the Rook by 1...exd4, see the Variation.
---------------------------------------------------------
Black is up the Exchange, but the open position of his King, and the fact
that the White Bishop will soon prove to be active, gives Labourdonnais
excellent chances to hold the game.

2.Rd2 gets the Rook out of danger and blocks the enemy Rook's attack on the
White King. Though White will end up down an Exchange, the open nature of
the Black King will make any winning chances problematic.

2...Rxd2+ exchanges pieces in the hope that the extra Exchange will prove
to be sufficient for the victory.

---------------------------------------------------------
The critical juncture has passed and now White is simply an Exchange
down. However, he has every reason to hope for a draw because the enemy
pawn on b7 is vulnerable to an attack by the White Bishop and the Black
King is always in danger of being checked. In the actual game, Black was
not able to find a winning idea.

3.Kxd2 is clearly the only sane choice.

3...Rd8+ gets the Rook into the game and continues the attack against the
White King.

White wants to get out of check in such a way that precludes the Black
Queen from jumping into the attack with gain of time. White also wants to
hold firmly onto his pieces and pawns on f2 and f3. Find a move that
accomplishes all these goals. 

4.Ke2! gets out of check and stops the Black Queen from jumping into the
assault with a check of its own. When you are defending, make sure
everything is well guarded. 

4...Qh6 threatens a big check on d2.

5.Qc3! keeps an eye on both d2 and c1. It also forces Black to react to the
newly created threat against the e5- pawn. Mixing defense and attack like
this is usually a good idea. 

5...Qg7 passively defends e5. Black was probably a bit upset here since his
hoped for win was not proving to be such an easy acquisition. 

The White Queen already stands well. Can the position of the other White
forces be improved?

6.Be4! firmly blocks the e-pawn, takes aim at the Black King and frees the
third rank for a possible Qh3+. After 6.Be4 the White army is shown to be
extremely well coordinated.

6...Kg8 steps off the h-file but the active White army is now posing too
many problems for Black to have any real chances for a win. Black rejected
6...Qg4+ since 7.Bf3! threatens the Queen and both pawns on b7 and
e5. Black would then have nothing better than a repetition of moves by
7...Qg7. 

7.Qb3+ creates an immediate draw since a perpetual check or the win of the
b7-pawn is now forced.

7...Kf8 fails but so does 7...Kh8 8.Qh3+ and 7...Qf7 8.Qxf7+ followed by
9.Bxb7. Black can no longer hope to win the game and he only plays another
move or two due to an overwhelming sense of depression. 

8.Qf3+! forces the win of the b7-pawn. This leads to an easy draw for White
because Rook vs. Bishop (with no pawns on the board) is known as unwinnable
for the Rook.

8...Qf7 is as good as anything. Black has already resigned himself to the
upcoming declaration of peace. 

9.Bxb7 eats the pawn and keeps the Black King on f8. 

9...Qxf3+ exchanges the Queens but forces the White King to a better
post. Remember that Kings love to advance once an endgame is reached. 

10.Kxf3 brings the White King closer to the center. The players agreed to a
draw here since Black can no longer hope to win the game since he has
nothing left to attack: White's King is safe (on e4 or e3), his f2-pawn is
safely defended by the King (and it may advance to f4 and exchange itself
for the e5-pawn) and his b5-pawn can either advance and threaten to promote
or be safely defended by Bc6.

Your result:
Score: 93%
