* Mutual Confusion! Cok iyi derseler var bunda :-)
"Pawn endings: Begineer to Expert" ders surusunun sonu!
http://www.chess.com/chessmentor/view_lesson?id=446

Grandmaster Andy Soltis wrote in his recent endgame book that one should
not trade down into a king and pawn ending unless one could safely bet
one's first-born on the outcome of the game. In the game Wolski-Peters,
American Open 1997, White just traded rooks from a slightly better position
to reach an unclear pawn ending. I, playing White, anticipated a very long
line which ended in Black drawing only after most precise play. However, I
had missed a minor detail in my calculations. 
---------------------------------------------------------
Black is up a pawn, but both his pawns on d4 and a4 are weak.

** .. Bariz hamleler.. siyah f3'e saldiriyor, beyaz da a4'e.
1...Kg5 activates the king and eyes White's f3-pawn.
2.Kxd4 captures the bothersome d-pawn. If 2.f4+, then 2...Kg4 is fine for
Black. 
---------------------------------------------------------
Black's king is penetrating into White's position.

2...Kf4 makes sure that White does not keep the passed f- pawn.

3.Kc3 aims for the lonely a4-pawn.
---------------------------------------------------------
** This is the critical moment of the game.** 
3...b5!! was played instantly by IM Jack Peters. He thought this was the
only move to secure the draw for Black, but it turns out that Black is
winning now. I had only expected 3...Kxf3, when Black would be able to draw
only with best defense, e.g., 4.Kb4 Ke4 5.Kxa4 Kd4 6.Kb5 Kd3 7.b3 Kc3 8.Kc6
Kxb3 9.Kxc7 Kxc4 10.Kxd6 b5 11.Ke5 b4 12.d6 b3 13.d7 b2 14.d8=Q b1=Q
15.Qc8+ Kb3! (this is the only move that draws for Black).  

Sometimes when one looks far ahead in a long line, one can miss an
important detail early on. 

4.cxb5 is White's best try. If 4.Kb4, then Black would soon win the d5-pawn
after 4...bxc4. In the game I resigned here, being low on time and not
seeing any hope. However, when I extended my hand toward Peters, he thought
that I wanted to offer him a draw and demanded that I first make a move! It
was in the late evening hours and we were both getting a bit confused. I
looked at the board for another minute or two and then insisted on my
resignation! Of course, I should have played 4.cxb5 first, and then see
whether he would find the win.
4...Kxf3 first captures the outside passer. If 4.Ke5?, then 5.Kc4 would put
Black in zugzwang. 
5.Kb4 looks for active counterplay. If 5.Kd3, then 5...Kf4 6.Kd4 Kf5 puts
White in zugzwang, e.g., 7.Kd3 Ke5 8.Kc4 Ke4. 
---------------------------------------------------------
Black now has a clear winning plan.
5...Ke4 attacks the isolated d5-pawn. Now it becomes clear why 3...b5!! was
such a great move. Black will soon have a passed d-pawn.
6.Kxa4 first removes the a4-pawn. If 6.b6, then 6...cxb6 7.Kb5 Kxd5 wins
for Black. 
---------------------------------------------------------
Now it looks deceptively simple.
6...Kxd5 wins the isolated d5-pawn and gives Black a passed d-pawn.
7.b6! is White's only chance. After I resigned a few moves earlier, both
Peters and GM Pavel Blatny thought that I could have drawn with this move. 
---------------------------------------------------------
White's counterplay is almost enough for a draw.
7...cxb6 is forced.
8.Kb5 attacks the b6-pawn.
---------------------------------------------------------
White's counterplay is almost enough for a draw.
8...Ke4 gets out of the way of the d-pawn and covers many squares along the
pawn's traveling route. For that reason 8...Ke6? 9.Kxb6 d5 10.Kc5 only
draws. 
9.Kxb6 wins the b6-pawn.
---------------------------------------------------------
Both pawns are five steps away from queening, but White's king is in the
way of its pawn.
9...d5 gets the pawn going.
10.b4 also advances a pawn.
---------------------------------------------------------
Both pawns are four steps away from queening, but White's king is in the
way of its pawn.
10...d4 gets the pawn closer.
11.b5 also advances a pawn.
---------------------------------------------------------
White's king is in the way of its pawn.
After 11...d3, it becomes clear that Black will queen first.
12.Kc7 steps out of the way of the pawn. Any other king move would meet the
same plan.
---------------------------------------------------------
When playing king and pawn endings, it's important to know how a queen does
against a pawn on the seventh rank supported by its king.
12...d2 gets ready for promotion.
13.b6 advances the pawn again.
---------------------------------------------------------
A queen wins against a passed b-pawn on the seventh rank supported by its
king. But if White had an a-pawn or a c-pawn instead, the position would be
a draw due to stalemate resources.
13...d1=Q queens the pawn.
