* REMEMBER SPACE!
* SPACE ADVANTAGE :-)
http://www.chess.com/chessmentor/view_lesson?id=7074
** It's intuitive that having more space than your opponent constitutes an
advantage. One of the most important aspects of a space advantage is that
you have more room than your opponent to maneuver; the player with a space
disadvantage finds his pieces cramped and unable to keep up with his
opponent's maneuvers. 
---------------------------------------------------------
A quick glance shows that White enjoys a huge space advantage, mostly due
to the blocked pawn chains - where White's is far further advanced than
Black's. Note that the Black queen and rooks can hardly move; the Black
knight can only go on the circuit d8-f7-h8 and back again; and the bishop
can only shuffle behind the pawn chain on the last two ranks. Meanwhile,
White's pieces enjoy total freedom. However, to actually win the game White
needs to attack and win a weak point in Black's position. To this end, you
need to identify Black's weak pawn and send your knight on a maneuver to
attack it. Try to find this maneuver.

** 2
Great job! The b7 pawn - the base of Black's pawn chain - is his only
attackable weakness. Therefore White sends the knight on a trip to a5 to
attack this pawn. Black has three moves to prepare for this, but due to his
extremely cramped position his pieces are not able to arrange an adequate
defense. 

** 3, 4
Unfortunately for Black, freeing the d8 square for his knight on this or
the next move by playing ...Rd7 fails to Ra8, trapping the Black
queen. This is a direct result of his cramped position.

White continues the knight maneuver.
** 5, 6
In preparation for the attack on b7, Black frees the d8 square for the
knight. There is no other way to guard b7, which - if it falls - will cause
Black's whole position to collapse. 

The knight takes aim at b7, and due to Black's cramped position he is
unable to get his pieces in the proper defensive positions in time. 

** 7,8,9
Very good - White breaks through to the base of Black's pawn chain, b7,
using the pin on the 7th rank. The other winning method was 4.Nxb7 Nxb7
5.Ba6, when Black loses material. 

Black has no other option, since his pieces are not able to defend b7, and
if it falls his position will also be hopeless. 

The point of the previous move. White still has not won any material, but
he has invaded the Black position and destroyed the pawn chain - soon
everything will fall apart. 

** 10
White threatened 6.Rxh7. After 5...Nf7 one way (of many) to win is 6.Rb7
Qa8 7.Ra7 Qb8 8.Rxa6, followed by the invasion of White's heavy pieces and
the advance of the passed b-pawn. 
---------------------------------------------------------
White has broken through, but now needs to remove a crucial defender which
will cause the Black position to fall apart immediately. 

** 11
Very good. The knight might have been a sorry piece, but it was the only
thing left holding Black's position together. 

** 12
White captures another pawn and regains the exchange next move due to the
fork. In view of White's two connected passed pawns, which will quickly
advance and win material, Black resigned. This famous example (from a game
by Capablanca) teaches several things about a space advantage: 1) A space
advantage usually results in the cramping of the opponent's pieces; 2) It
is best not to exchange pieces when you have a space advantage; and 3) To
exploit a space advantage you need to find a weakness in your opponent's
position which you can attack. Quite frequently your opponent cannot defend
because his pieces are "tripping over each other" and wrestling each other
for the critical squares. 

